    <title>String Variables</title>
    <briefdescription>
    </briefdescription>
    <detaileddescription>
<para>String variables are represented by any variable with the suffix <computeroutput>$</computeroutput>, e.g. <computeroutput>C$</computeroutput> or <computeroutput>MYVAR$</computeroutput>. They are stored as <bold>null-terminated C-style sequences</bold> of <bold>8-bit ASCII characters</bold>.</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
<sect1 id="type-string_1examples-179_1s1"><sect2 id="type-string_1examples-179_1s2"><sect3 id="type-string_1examples-179">
<title>Examples</title><para><programlisting filename=".basic"><codeline><highlight class="normal">name$<sp/>=<sp/>&quot;Retro<sp/>Rocket&quot;</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">PRINT<sp/>&quot;Hello,<sp/>&quot;;<sp/>name$</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para><programlisting filename=".basic"><codeline><highlight class="normal">REM<sp/>Concatenate<sp/>strings</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">first$<sp/>=<sp/>&quot;Hello&quot;</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">second$<sp/>=<sp/>&quot;World&quot;</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">PRINT<sp/>first$<sp/>+<sp/>&quot;<sp/>&quot;<sp/>+<sp/>second$</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para><programlisting filename=".basic"><codeline><highlight class="normal">REM<sp/>Accessing<sp/>characters</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">ch$<sp/>=<sp/>LEFT$(name$,<sp/>1)</highlight></codeline>
<codeline><highlight class="normal">PRINT<sp/>&quot;First<sp/>character<sp/>=<sp/>&quot;;<sp/>ch$</highlight></codeline>
</programlisting></para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
</sect3></sect2></sect1>
<sect1 id="type-string_1notes-183_1s1"><sect2 id="type-string_1notes-183_1s2"><sect3 id="type-string_1notes-183">
<title>Notes</title><para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>Strings are mutable and can be reassigned at any time.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Maximum length depends on available memory.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Operations such as concatenation (<computeroutput>+</computeroutput>), substring (<ref refid="LEFT" kindref="compound">LEFT$</ref> / <ref refid="RIGHT" kindref="compound">RIGHT$</ref> / <ref refid="MID" kindref="compound">MID$</ref>), and trimming (<ref refid="TRIM" kindref="compound">TRIM$</ref>) are supported.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Null termination is internal — it is not visible during normal BASIC operations.</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para><hruler/>
</para>
